(this["webpackJsonpbrown-edu-orchestra"]=this["webpackJsonpbrown-edu-orchestra"]||[]).push([[35],{115:function(e,t,a){"use strict";a.r(t),a.d(t,"readingTime",(function(){return o})),a.d(t,"meta",(function(){return i})),a.d(t,"default",(function(){return h})),a.d(t,"tableOfContents",(function(){return l})),a.d(t,"frontMatter",(function(){return c}));var n=a(11),r=(a(2),a(1)),o={text:"6 min read",minutes:5.78,time:346800,words:1156},i={title:"BUO Soloist Spotlight: Yiyun Li",subtitle:"Featuring Yiyun Li '26",author:{name:"Zo\xeb Schwartz",uid:"zoeschwartz1",email:"zoe_m_schwartz@brown.edu",browndirectory:"ea3eb164-9874-4a22-bf09-ffb37cbe8f0a"},topic:"Blog",date:"2026-03-16",image:{url:"/images/uploads/yiyun_blog_header.jpg"},path:"/news/2026-03-16/buo-soloist-spotlight-yiyun-li"},s={meta:i};function h(e){var t=e.components,a=Object(n.a)(e,["components"]);return Object(r.a)("wrapper",Object.assign({},s,a,{components:t,mdxType:"MDXLayout"}),Object(r.a)("p",null,"On Saturday, March 14, those who were lucky enough to acquire a ticket to the Brown University Orchestra concert will have the opportunity to hear the bubbling laughter, swooping gestures, and poignant lyricism of Jean Fran\xe7aix\u2019s Clarinet Concerto. The piece will be performed by the BUO\u2019s dedicated clarinetist and concerto competition winner, Yiyun Li. Yiyun is a senior from Baltimore, Maryland who studies music and IAPA (International and Public Affairs) and enjoys fiber arts, hiking, cooking, and crafting charcuterie boards. I recently sat down with her to discuss her musical journey and her connection to the Fran\xe7aix concerto."),Object(r.a)("p",null,"Although Yiyun had taken piano lessons since she was five, her love of the clarinet began in fifth grade. Her elementary school encouraged its students to choose any band or orchestra instrument to learn for the year. The exploratory music program allowed them to try out the clarinet, violin, and trumpet ahead of time, and Yiyun \u201c","[","could only] make sounds on the clarinet, so ","[","she] chose that one.\u201d She explains that her relationship with the clarinet was quite different from her experience with piano: \u201cWhen I was learning piano\u2026 I always thought of it as the instrument that my parents made me learn. I didn\u2019t like it as much, just because I felt like I was forced into it a little bit. But with the clarinet, since I chose it, I thought it was super fun. I remember I really liked learning random pop songs.\u201d Yiyun credits quite a bit of her passion for the clarinet to her private teacher back in Maryland, who she \u201cwas really close with\u201d and \u201cdefinitely played a big role in ","[","her] liking the instrument and wanting to pursue it more.\u201d As Yiyun entered middle and high school, she found herself presented with more opportunities for clarinet performance and ensemble experience. She participated in bands and orchestras outside of her school, such as Maryland All-County Band and the Baltimore Symphony Youth Orchestra.\xa0"),Object(r.a)("p",null,"Since orchestral performance was such a core part of her high school experience, she knew without a doubt that she wanted to join the Brown University Orchestra; Yiyun has been a member of the BUO for all four years of her time at university. However, Yiyun has a broader musical life at Brown than being a wonderful orchestral clarinetist (and bass clarinetist). She has participated in the Chamber Music Program and has taken private lessons with Karen Heninger through the Applied Music Program. Her musical experience expands beyond the classical world; she is currently \u201csort of playing part-time with the Brown Jazz Band,\u201d and has been in Em\u2019s Femmes, a jazz/pop band for underrepresented genders in jazz, since sophomore year. She also provides free clarinet lessons to members of the Providence community through the Community Music Project at Haven United Methodist Church.\xa0"),Object(r.a)("p",null,"Yiyun has expressed great joy and gratitude toward her musical life at Brown and her time in the orchestra. She \u201cjust really ","[","enjoys] the orchestra community at Brown\u2026 a lot of ","[","her] closest friends are either in orchestra or are people that ","[","she] met through orchestra.\u201d She states that the orchestra is \u201ca very supportive space overall,\u201d where everyone \u201cjust really likes music and really likes to play together,\u201d fostering a wonderful sense of community. She also recognizes that her academic experience as a music concentrator has positively impacted her life as a performer: \u201cTheory classes and musicology classes\u2026 have added a lot more depth to how I think about music. I definitely notice that the theory background enhances my playing\u2026 The musicology classes that I\u2019ve taken\u2026 make me think a lot more about the background of a piece and the intention behind it\u2026 All of that has made me grow as a musician in how I approach music.\u201d\xa0"),Object(r.a)("p",null,"For Yiyun, the draw of the Fran\xe7aix Clarinet Concerto \u201cwas that the piece sounded like it would be a lot of fun, and ","[","she] knew it would be a challenge to learn.\u201d She was fascinated by the \u201creally goofy-sounding characters and bizarre things that ","[","Fran\xe7aix] wrote into the concerto.\u201d Yiyun remarks that composers like Fran\xe7aix \u201cwill write the craziest, weirdest technical passages\u2026 things that sound super modern and crazy, but then at the same time they\u2019ll write the most gorgeous, lyrical slow movements.\u201d In the Fran\xe7aix, \u201cmost of the movements are very technical and kind of all-over-the-place, but then the third movement is this beautiful, gorgeous, slow movement.\u201d Her favorite part of the concerto is this contrast, specifically \u201cthe transition between the third and fourth movements, because the ending of the third movement is super ethereal and disappears into the atmosphere, and then the beginning of the fourth movement is crazy, loud, and ","[","blaringly] high\u2014it almost sounds like a laugh.\u201d She finds it \u201creally amusing\u201d to go between those movements, and also thinks that \u201cthe fourth movement in general is very clown-like and really funny to listen to.\u201d Yiyun remarks that \u201cFran\xe7aix knew that he was writing ","[","a goofy] piece\u2026 In general, ","[","he] was a very carefree and sort of silly composer.\u201d Although she wishes she could ask Fran\xe7aix his inspirations and intentions behind the piece, she supposes that he wanted it to be both technically challenging and amusing to listen to: \u201cIt\u2019s meant to make you laugh.\u201d\xa0"),Object(r.a)("p",null,"The piece is a poignant representation of her growth as a clarinetist: \u201cI remember really distinctly this one time I had a conversation with a friend and ","[","they asked], \u2018Do you feel like there\u2019s any music in the clarinet repertoire that would be too hard for you?\u2019 I ","[","said] \u2018Oh yeah, for sure,\u2019 and one of the pieces that I named was the Fran\xe7aix.\u201d Before diving into the Fran\xe7aix, she had never learned a complete concerto, only individual movements or shorter show pieces. Now, she has not only learned the entire concerto but will perform it as an orchestral soloist, accompanied by her proud friends and classmates. She explains the surreal feeling of playing with an orchestral accompaniment: \u201cPlaying with orchestra\u2026 you\u2019re enveloped by so many other musicians\u2026 to feel all the different sounds and timbres and parts surrounding you\u2026 it just feels super cool.\u201d However, she admits that the new setting \u201cdefinitely presents a lot of challenges\u2026 Rehearsing with the orchestra has been such a call-out to all the spots that ","[","she tends to rush]. Having to adjust to so many people who are accompanying you is certainly a different challenge.\u201d In my humble opinion, I think she has risen to the challenge wonderfully."),Object(r.a)("p",null,"After graduating this spring, Yiyun will sadly be leaving the BUO and the \u201creally immersive music experience\u201d she has had at Brown. However, she is determined to fashion for herself a \u201cfruitful music experience post-grad\u201d alongside her intended work in health or food policy. We wish her all the best in finding her way in the world and keeping music close to her heart!"))}h.isMDXComponent=!0;var l=function(){return[]},c={}}}]);
